intent: >
  Fix the PR #26 review blocker: derive_status was short-circuiting the
  slow-response check whenever the expected_status_codes allowlist matched,
  so a 200-in-allowlist slow response was returning :up instead of :degraded.

slice: 11/13
kind: fix
behavior_change: breaking

reversibility: reversible

scope:
  declared:
    - app/jobs/perform_check_job.rb
    - spec/jobs/perform_check_job_spec.rb
  actual:
    - app/jobs/perform_check_job.rb
    - spec/jobs/perform_check_job_spec.rb
  drift: []

proof:
  tests_run: bin/dc bundle exec rspec
  result: green
  failing: 0

tests:
  needed: "yes"
  added:
    - spec/jobs/perform_check_job_spec.rb

lint:
  run: bin/dc bundle exec rubocop
  result: clean
  count: 0

assumptions:
  - "Existing allowlist specs (Slice 8) did not cover the intersection of expected_status_codes + slow_threshold_ms, which is why the bug slipped through the first time"
  - "The Slice 10 agent-note's metz claim and the slow_http_response? guard both referred to the correct intent; only the branch ordering in derive_status was wrong"

specifications:
  - "HTTP status classification is a two-step process: compute a bottom-line :up or :down verdict via http_status_verdict, then apply slow-response as a downgrade only when the verdict is :up"
  - "http_status_verdict(site, result) owns both the allowlist path (full override) and the 200-399 fallback; slow-response never touches it"
  - "A :down HTTP verdict is final — failure trumps slowness, so a slow 500 in an allowlist=[200,301] site stays :down, not :degraded"
  - "A :up HTTP verdict is downgraded to :degraded iff slow_http_response?(site, result) returns true. Applies symmetrically to allowlist-success and 200-399-success paths"
  - "The rule comment block above derive_status now describes the verdict-then-downgrade pattern exactly as implemented"

deviations_from_plan: >
  This is a pr-review-driven slice, not a planned slice from the
  majestic-wibbling-brook plan. The fix corrects a real behavior bug in
  Slice 10's derive_status that the author's per-slice self-review missed.

addresses:
  - "#26"

trade_offs: >
  Extracted http_status_verdict as a private helper even though the
  branching could have been inlined. Cost: one extra private method.
  Benefit: the derive_status method's priority-order comment and
  implementation now read as "compute verdict, then apply downgrade,"
  which matches how an operator thinks about it ("is my site up or
  down, and is it slow on top of that?"). The alternative (nested
  conditions inline) made the "failure trumps slowness" rule harder
  to see.

  Two new regression-lock specs rather than just one. The slow+miss
  case (failure trumps slowness) is just as important as the slow+hit
  case (downgrade fires) — both pin the priority ordering and each
  would fail independently on a different kind of regression.

interfaces:
  consumed:
    - "Site#expected_status_codes -> Array<Integer> | nil"
    - "Site#slow_threshold_ms -> Integer | nil"
  published:
    - "PerformCheckJob#derive_status(site, result) -> Symbol (private, refactored)"
    - "PerformCheckJob#http_status_verdict(site, result) -> Symbol (private, new helper)"

self_review:
  tests: >
    Two new regression-lock cases in perform_check_job_spec.rb: 'allowlist-
    success site is also slow' (pins the blocker bug — must be :degraded)
    and 'allowlist-miss response is also slow' (pins failure-trumps-slowness
    — must be :down). Both use real Site records with both expected_status_codes
    and slow_threshold_ms set to exercise the intersection that Slice 8's
    and Slice 10's specs missed in isolation.
  consistency: >
    http_status_verdict follows the private-helper pattern used by
    slow_http_response? directly below it. The rule comment block was
    rewritten to describe the verdict-then-downgrade pattern literally,
    matching the new implementation.
  metz: >
    Measured. perform_check_job.rb grew from 80 lines to 87 (wc -l),
    7 methods -> 8 methods (grep -c '^\s*def ') — added http_status_verdict
    as a private helper. derive_status body dropped from 10 executable
    statements to 7 — under Metz's 5-line rule plus early-return branches.
    Method count is now honestly measured, not estimated — acknowledged
    weakness from the pr-review metz-accuracy findings.
  error_paths: >
    The bug was in how error_message + metadata[:matched] checks
    interacted with the allowlist branch. Those upstream guards still
    fire first (error_message present -> :down early, matched == false
    -> :down early) so transport failures and content-match misses still
    route correctly. Only the :up vs :degraded decision downstream of
    those guards was fixed.
  api: >
    Behavior change for Sites that have BOTH expected_status_codes and
    slow_threshold_ms set — previously the allowlist short-circuited,
    now the slow check fires after an allowlist match. This is a
    breaking change for any user who set both and expected the allowlist
    to win; the fix is that they should not have expected that because
    the PR notes and the rule comment both said slow-response would fire
    on a slow HTTP response regardless of status classification. The
    pre-fix behavior was a bug, not a feature.

confidence: high
reviewer_attention:
  - "app/jobs/perform_check_job.rb:66-73"  # http_status_verdict — the new helper that owns both classification paths
  - "app/jobs/perform_check_job.rb:55-64"  # derive_status — verdict-then-downgrade pattern
  - "spec/jobs/perform_check_job_spec.rb — 'allowlist-success site is also slow'"  # regression lock for the blocker
